# 4. Supporting Code for Section 1.2 — Problem Description

The Problem Description argues that Spotify's audio features are poorly
understood in how they vary across genres and relate to one another, and that
this gap has real consequences for recommendation systems. Before writing that
argument, I needed to verify that our data actually showed this kind of
complexity — that features did behave differently across genres and that some
features were indeed redundant.

## 4.1 Genre Distribution — Is the Dataset Balanced?

A key point in the Problem Description is that the dataset has real-world
relevance across many genres. I checked the genre distribution to understand
the scope of what we were analyzing.

```{r genre-distribution}
genre_counts <- spotify_df %>%
  count(genre, sort = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(
    Percentage    = round(n / sum(n) * 100, 1),
    Cumulative    = cumsum(Percentage)
  ) %>%
  rename(Genre = genre, Track_Count = n)

kable(genre_counts,
      caption = "Genre distribution across the dataset")
```

```{r top5-share}
top5_pct <- sum(genre_counts$Percentage[1:5])
cat("The top 5 genres account for", top5_pct, "% of all tracks.\n")
cat("This concentration shaped how the problem was framed in Section 1.2.\n")
```

## 4.2 Feature Range Check — Do Features Vary Meaningfully?

Part of the Problem Description establishes that these features are worth
studying because they do vary. I confirmed the range and spread of core
features to back that up.

```{r feature-ranges}
bounded_features <- c("danceability", "energy", "valence",
                      "acousticness", "speechiness",
                      "instrumentalness", "liveness")

range_report <- sapply(spotify_df[bounded_features], function(x) {
  c(Min    = round(min(x, na.rm = TRUE), 3),
    Max    = round(max(x, na.rm = TRUE), 3),
    Mean   = round(mean(x, na.rm = TRUE), 3),
    SD     = round(sd(x, na.rm = TRUE), 3))
})

kable(t(range_report),
      caption = "Feature ranges — confirmed meaningful variation across all features")
```

## 4.3 Energy vs. Loudness — Are Some Features Redundant?

The Problem Description mentions that some features may capture overlapping
dimensions, which creates issues for downstream systems. I confirmed the
energy-loudness redundancy here before making that claim in writing.

```{r energy-loudness}
r_el <- cor(spotify_df$energy, spotify_df$loudness,
            use = "complete.obs", method = "pearson")

cat("Pearson correlation (energy vs. loudness):", round(r_el, 3), "\n")
cat("This positive relationship of r =", round(r_el, 3),
    "supports the claim that some features are partially redundant.\n")
```

