# 7. Supporting Visualization

I produced this visualization for my own reference while writing the
Limitations section. It shows the mean value of each bounded audio feature
across the entire dataset, making the high-energy, high-danceability skew
immediately visible and giving me a concrete reference point for the bias
discussion in Section 6.

```{r feature-means-plot, fig.cap="Mean values of bounded audio features — produced to inform Limitations writing."}
bounded <- c("danceability", "energy", "speechiness",
             "acousticness", "instrumentalness", "liveness", "valence")

feature_means <- spotify_df %>%
  select(all_of(bounded)) %>%
  summarise(across(everything(), ~round(mean(., na.rm = TRUE), 3))) %>%
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "Feature", values_to = "Mean_Value")

ggplot(feature_means, aes(x = reorder(Feature, Mean_Value),
                          y = Mean_Value, fill = Mean_Value)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_text(aes(label = Mean_Value), hjust = -0.2, size = 3.5) +
  coord_flip(ylim = c(0, 1.15)) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "#AED6F1", high = "#1A5276") +
  labs(
    title = "Mean values of bounded audio features (0–1 scale)",
    subtitle = "Produced to assess dataset skew while writing Limitations",
    x = "Audio Feature",
    y = "Mean Value (0–1)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))
```

**What this showed me:** Energy has the highest mean of all bounded features,
confirming the dataset is dominated by high-intensity music. Instrumentalness
and speechiness are both very low, meaning most tracks contain vocals and
minimal spoken word content. These observations directly informed the
dataset bias discussion in Section 6.

