# 8. Sections I Wrote in the Team Paper

## 8.1 Section 1.2 — Problem Description

Music streaming platforms like Spotify generate enormous volumes of listening
data, yet the underlying audio characteristics that define how songs are
perceived and categorized remain poorly understood. Spotify assigns each track
quantifiable audio features including danceability, energy, valence, tempo,
loudness, and acousticness, but it is not well established how these features
vary across genres or how strongly they relate to one another. Without a clear
understanding of these relationships, playlist curation, mood-based
recommendation, and genre classification systems are built on assumptions
rather than evidence. This paper addresses that gap by conducting a structured
exploratory data analysis of Spotify audio features across 15 genres using
42,303 tracks. Understanding these patterns matters because it has practical
implications for how recommendation algorithms are designed, how independent
artists position their music, and how researchers study cultural and musical
trends over time.

---

## 8.2 Section 6 — Limitations and Future Work

This study has several notable limitations that readers should consider when
interpreting findings. The dataset sourced from Kaggle in 2020 is not a
balanced representation of all music on Spotify. It is dominated by hip-hop,
techno, techhouse, and psytrance, meaning distributions of danceability,
energy, and tempo reflect those specific communities rather than music as a
whole. Classical, jazz, folk, ambient, and gospel music are entirely absent,
so conclusions about typical audio feature values should not be generalized
to all recorded music. The data was also collected in 2020, and genre audio
profiles evolve over time, meaning the findings may not fully reflect the
current state of any genre. Because this is an exploratory study, all
identified relationships are correlational rather than causal, and Spotify's
feature extraction process is proprietary, introducing an unresolvable layer
of uncertainty in what each metric truly measures.

Future work should expand the dataset to include a more balanced and diverse
range of genres to test whether patterns like the energy-loudness correlation
hold broadly or are specific to high-energy dance communities. Applying
supervised machine learning models such as random forests or gradient boosting
could allow researchers to move beyond description toward prediction, testing
whether audio features alone can classify genre or mood reliably. Integrating
user behavioral data such as skip rates and time-of-day listening patterns
alongside audio features would create a richer picture of how sonic
characteristics translate into real listener experience. A longitudinal
analysis tracking changes in genre audio profiles from 2015 to the present
would also offer meaningful insight into how cultural forces shape the sound
of popular music over time.

---

## 8.3 Section 7 — Conclusion

This study explored Spotify audio features across 42,303 tracks to better
understand how musical characteristics are distributed across genres and how
they relate to one another. The findings showed that danceability, energy, and
tempo are all shaped by the genre makeup of the dataset, with most songs
scoring high in danceability and energy, and tempo splitting into two distinct
clusters reflecting the different rhythmic styles of hip-hop near 125 BPM and
techno near 150 BPM. Energy and loudness were found to have a strong positive
relationship, meaning that as a song becomes more intense it also tends to be
louder, suggesting these two features partially measure the same underlying
quality. Genre proved to be a reliable predictor of danceability, with
techhouse and underground rap consistently scoring higher than trance and
hardstyle, though overlapping ranges across genres indicate that danceability
alone cannot classify a track without the support of other features. The
correlation analysis confirmed that energy and loudness are the most closely
related features at r = 0.60, while most other feature pairs remained largely
independent, showing that Spotify's audio features generally do a good job of
measuring different aspects of music separately. Overall, this project
demonstrates that exploratory data analysis is a powerful and accessible way
to uncover meaningful patterns in large music datasets without needing complex
models, and the insights gained here lay a solid foundation for future research
into music recommendation, genre classification, and the deeper connection
between the sound of music and how people experience it emotionally.

