# 10. Reflection and Learning Outcomes

Working as the Writing Lead gave me a different perspective on the project than
my teammates. While they focused on building the code and visuals, my job was
to make sure every sentence in the paper could be defended with specific numbers
rather than general impressions from looking at a plot.

The biggest challenge was writing the Limitations section. It required thinking
critically about what our findings could not claim rather than just what they
could. Once I ran the genre distribution check and saw how concentrated the
data was in a handful of high-energy genres, it became clear that every strong
claim in the paper needed a qualifier about generalizability.

Writing the Conclusion also pushed me to be precise. It was not enough to say
"energy and loudness are related" — I needed to say r = 0.60, name the
direction, and explain what it means in plain language. Running the verification
code first made that possible.

If I were to extend this work I would want to test whether the patterns we
found hold in a more balanced dataset, and I would want to explore longitudinal
changes in genre audio profiles over time, which a single 2020 snapshot
cannot capture.

